# WORKFLOW RULES [CRITICAL]

**Rule 3 [CRITICAL]:** Every response MUST end with `Agents involved: [agent names]` (or `Agents involved: None (direct tool usage)`). Transparency, accountability, traceability. Violation is a CRITICAL ERROR.

The rules below are one-line pointers. Full bodies live in the agent / skill / command files referenced - those are the canonical executors.

**Rule 32 [CRITICAL] - Bug validation.** All bug validation goes through the **`bug-validator`** subagent (`.cursor/agents/bug-validator.md`): extract expected behavior -> Confluence (MCP) -> codebase (READ-ONLY) -> 5-verdict matrix (VALID / NEEDS CLARIFICATION / NEEDS APPROVAL / NOT VALID / INSUFFICIENT EVIDENCE) -> chat reply with confidence (Rule CONF.1). Disk file only on `/report` or explicit save. NEVER modify code during validation.

**Rule 33 [CRITICAL] - Database queries.** All Phoenix DB queries go through the matching `PostgreSQL{Env}` MCP server using the connect-first workflow. Use the **exact** environment the user named. Credentials live ONLY in MCP server config - never in rules / skills / code / chat. Full DB.0-DB.6 workflow + SQL templates: **`phoenix-database` skill** (`.cursor/skills/phoenix-database/SKILL.md` + `references/`).

**Rule 35 [CRITICAL] - Test case generation.** When the user requests test cases, run **`cross-dependency-finder`** subagent FIRST (Rule 35a), then call **`test-case-generator`** subagent with `context['cross_dependency_data']`. Test-case-generator MUST first read `Cursor-Project/config/playwright_generation/playwright instructions/` (`project-description.md` -> `general-rules.md` -> `test-writing-rules.instructions.md` -> `SKILL.md`, then any other `*.md` alphabetically), then save as TWO files - `test_cases/Backend/<Topic>.md` (TC-BE-N) and `test_cases/Frontend/<Topic>.md` (TC-FE-N) - per `Test_case_template.md`, with mandatory creation-step preconditions (HOW to create every entity with endpoint + parameters; never just "entity exists"). NEVER skip cross-dependency-finder.

**Rule 35a [CRITICAL] - Jira-anchored cross-dependency (no local merge/git).** When the user provides a Jira/bug/task, the cross-dependency-finder MUST anchor on **Jira MCP + codebase (READ-ONLY) + shallow Confluence**. **Forbidden by default:** local `git log --grep` / merge history scans for the ticket key, the removed `CrossDependency_GitSnapshot.ps1`, conditional git sync triggered only by cross-dep. **Optional only on explicit user request:** GitLab MCP read-only for MRs/merges. `technical_details` come from Jira + codebase, not merge archaeology.

**Rule 36 [CRITICAL] - EnergoTS Playwright run.** All requests to run Playwright tests from EnergoTS go through the **`energo-ts-run`** workflow (`.cursor/agents/energo-ts-run.md`, `.cursor/commands/energo-ts-run.md`). Tests run **only from the `cursor` branch** (Rule ENERGOTS.0 in `.cursor/rules/integrations/energots_branch_lock.mdc`). No code modification; chat summary by default, file only on request (Rule 0.6).

**Rule 37 [CRITICAL] - HandsOff.** When the user provides a Jira ticket and invokes `/HandsOff` or `!HandsOff`, the **hands-off orchestrator** (`.cursor/commands/hands-off.md`, `.cursor/agents/hands-off.md`) runs the full flow without user intervention: (1) Jira MCP fetch -> (2) cross-dependency-finder -> (3) test-case-generator -> (4) energo-ts-test creates Playwright spec -> (4.5) playwright-test-validator (re-iterate (3)/(4) on fail, max iterations) -> (5) energo-ts-run executes (cursor branch only) -> (6) save `HandsOff reports/.../YYYY/<english-month>/<DD>/{JIRA_KEY}.md` per `Cursor-Project/reports/README.md` -> (7) send full report to Slack (Tester DM + #ai-report) -> (8) collect agent questions, tag each with the agent name, send after the report. No step is skipped.

Violation of any of the above is a CRITICAL SYSTEM ERROR.
